<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="chap-lebesgue-measure">
<title>Lebesgue Measure</title>
<introduction>

<blockquote>
<p><em><q>It may well be suspected that, had it not been for its prestigious name, [Riemann integration] would have been dropped long ago, for (with due reverence to Riemann’s genius) it is certainly quite clear to any working mathematician that nowadays such a <q>theory</q> has at best the importance of a mildly interesting exercise in the general theory of measure and integration.</q></em></p>
<attribution>
<p>Jean Dieudonné</p>
</attribution>
</blockquote>
</introduction>
<section xml:id="sec-Lebesgue">
<title>Lebesgue measure on <m>\mathbb{R}</m></title>
<p>We will now apply the Carathéodory-Hahn Theorem, <xref ref="thm-Car-ext-2" text="Theorem"/>, to define the promised Lebesgue measure. Our goal is to extend the length function <m>\ell</m> to a measure. In <xref ref="exam-interval-semiring" text="Example"/> (see <xref ref="exer-interval-semiring" text="Exercise"/>) we saw three different semirings of intervals. <xref ref="exer-length-premeasure" text="Exercise"/> tells us that <m>\ell</m> is a premeasure when restricted to each of these semirings. This gives three possibilities of where to apply the Carathéodory-Hahn theorem. The next proposition shows that this choice does not matter. We get the same outer measure no matter the choice.</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop-Lebesgue-outer-measure">
<p>Let <m>\mathcal{I}</m> be the semiring of all intervals in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>; let <m>\mathcal{I}_f</m> be the semiring of all finite length intervals; and let <m>\mathcal{I}_h</m> be the semiring of intervals of the form <m>(a,b]</m>, where <m>a,b \in \mathbb{R}</m> with <m>a \leq b</m>.
    Let <m>m^*</m> be the outer measure induced by <m>\ell</m> on <m>\mathcal{I}</m>; let <m>m_f^*</m> be the outer measure induced by <m>\ell</m> restricted to <m>\mathcal{I}_f</m>; and let <m>m_h^*</m> be the outer measure induced by <m>\ell</m> restricted to <m>\mathcal{I}_h</m>.
    Then for each <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>
<md> m^*(A) = m^*_f(A) = m^*_h(A) = \inf\left\{ \sum_{i=1}^\infty \ell((a_i,b_i) \colon A \subseteq \bigcup_{i=1}^\infty (a_i,b_i)\right\}.</md></p>
</proposition>
<proof>
<p>Since <m>\mathcal{I}_h \subseteq \mathcal{I}_f \subseteq \mathcal{I}</m> it follows that
<md> m^*(A) \leq m_f^*(A) \leq m_h^*(A)</md>
for all <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.
    Take any <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.
    If <m>m^*(A) = \infty</m>, then by the above inequalities, <m>m_f^*(A) = \infty</m> and <m>m_h^*(A) = \infty</m>.
    Suppose <m>m^*(A) &lt; \infty</m>.
    Fix <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>.
    There  exist intervals <m>\{I_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> such that <m>A \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty I_k</m> and
<md> m^*(A) + \varepsilon &gt; \sum_{k=1}^\infty \ell(I_k).</md>
As <m>m^*(A)&lt;\infty</m> it follows that <m>\sum_{k=1}^\infty \ell(I_k)&lt;\infty</m>, and so  <m>I_k</m> is of finite length for each <m>k</m>.
    Thus
<md>m^*(A)+\varepsilon &gt; \sum_{k=1}^\infty \ell(I_k) \geq m_f^*(A).</md>
As this holds for all <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>, it follows that <m>m^*(A) \geq m_f^*(A)</m>.
    Hence <m>m^* = m_f^*</m>.</p>
<p>We will now show that
<md>m^*(A) = \inf\left\{ \sum_{i=1}^\infty \ell((a_i,b_i) \colon A \subseteq \bigcup_{i=1}^\infty (a_i,b_i)\right\}.</md>
Let <m>m_0^*</m> denote the function
<md>m_0^*(A) = \inf\left\{ \sum_{i=1}^\infty \ell((a_i,b_i) \colon A \subseteq \bigcup_{i=1}^\infty (a_i,b_i)\right\}.</md>
Since <m>m^*=m_f^*</m> is an infimum over all covers by intervals of finite length, and <m>m_0^*</m> is an infimum over all covers by <em>open</em> intervals of finite length, it follows that <m>m^*(A) \leq m_0^*(A)</m> for all <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
<p>Now take any <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>. If <m>m^*(A) = \infty</m>, then <m>m_0^*(A)= \infty</m>.
    Suppose that <m>m^*(A) &lt;\infty</m>.
    Fix <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0</m>.
    Let <m>\{I_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> be a countable collection of finite length intervals such that <m>A \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty I_k</m> and</p>
<md> m^*(A) + \varepsilon &gt; \sum_{k=1}^\infty \ell(I_k).</md>
<p>For each <m>k</m>, let <m>a_k = \inf I_k</m> and let <m>b_k = \sup I_k</m>.
    Then
<md>A \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty I_k \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty (a_i - \frac{\varepsilon}{4^k}, b_i + \frac{\varepsilon}{4^k}). </md>
That is, <m>\{ (a_i - \frac{\varepsilon}{2^{k+1}}, b_i + \frac{\varepsilon}{2^{k+1}})\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> is a cover of <m>A</m> by open intervals of finite length.
    Thus
<md>
\begin{aligned}
m_0^*(A) &amp;\leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \ell((a_i - \frac{\varepsilon}{2^{k+1}}, b_i + \frac{\varepsilon}{2^{k+1}})) \\
        &amp; = \varepsilon + \sum_{k=1}^\infty\ell(I_k) \\
        &amp; &lt; m^*(A)+ 2 \varepsilon.
\end{aligned}
</md>
As the above inequality holds for all <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>, it follows that <m>m_0*(A) \leq m^*(A)</m>.
    Hence <m>m^* = m_0^*</m>.
    A similar argument shows that <m>m_h^* = m_0^*</m>.</p>
</proof>
<definition>
<p>The function <m>m^* \colon \mathcal{P}(\mathbb{R}) \rightarrow [0,\infty]</m> defined by</p>
<md> m^*(A) = \inf \left\{ \sum_{k=1}^\infty \ell(I_k) \colon A \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty I_k,\ \{I_k\}_{k=1}^\infty \text{ finite length open intervals}\right\}</md>
<p>is call the <em>Lebesgue outer measure</em> on <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.<idx><h>outer measure</h><h>Lebesgue outer measure</h></idx></p>
<p>The elements of the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra <m>\mathcal{M}</m> of <m>m^*</m>-measurable sets are called <em>Lebesgue measurable sets</em>.<idx><h>measurable set</h><h>Lebesgue measurable set</h></idx></p>
<p>The Carathéodory measure <m>m</m> got by restricting <m>m^*</m> to <m>\mathcal{M}</m> is called the <em>Lebesgue measure</em> on <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.<idx><h>Lebesgue measure</h></idx></p>
</definition>
<p><xref ref="prop-Lebesgue-outer-measure" text="Proposition"/> shows that the Lebesgue outer measure <m>m^*</m> is the outer measure induced by the length function <m>\ell</m>. Thus by the Carathéodory-Hahn theorem, <xref ref="thm-Car-ext-2" text="Theorem"/>, all intervals <m>I \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> are Lebesgue measurable, and <m>m(I) = \ell(I)</m>. Further, since <m>\ell</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite, the measure space <m>(\mathbb{R}, \mathcal{M}, m)</m> is a complete <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure space, and <m>m</m> is the unique extennsion of <m>\ell</m> to a measure on <m>\mathcal{M}</m>.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-countable-L-measurable">
<p>If <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> is a countable set, then <m>A</m> is Lebesgue measurable and <m>m(A) = 0</m>.</p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>Take any <m>b \in \mathbb{R}</m>. Then <m>\{b\}</m> can be written as a closed interval of <m>0</m> length</p>
<md> \{b\} = [b,b]. </md>
<p>Hence all singleton sets are Lebesgue measurable with Lebesgue measure <m>0</m>.
    Let <m>A</m> be a countable set.
    If <m>A</m> has <m>n</m> elements then we can write <m>A</m> as <m>A = \{a_1, \ldots, a_n\}</m>; if <m>A</m> is countably infinite we can write <m>A</m> as <m>A = \{a_1,a_2,\ldots\}</m>.
    Thus</p>
<md> A = \bigcup_{i=1}^n \{a_i\} \text{ or }A = \bigcup_{i=1}^\infty \{a_i\}.</md>
<p>In either case, <m>A</m> is a countable union of disjoint sets of measure <m>0</m>.
    Hence <m>m(A) = 0</m> by the countable additivity of <m>m</m>.</p>
</proof>
<remark>
<p><xref ref="thm-countable-L-measurable" text="Theorem"/> says that all countable sets have Lebesgue measure <m>0</m>.
    It does <em>not</em> say that if <m>m(A) = 0</m> then <m>A</m> is countable.
    We will see examples of uncountable sets of zero Lebesgue measure later.</p>
</remark>
<theorem xml:id="thm-Borel-Lebesgue-meas">
<p>All Borel sets in <m>\mathbb{R}</m> are Lebesgue measurable.
    That is, <m>\mathcal{B} \subseteq \mathcal{M}</m>.</p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>By the construction of <m>m</m> (i.e. the Carathéodory-Hahn theorem), all open intervals are Lebesgue measurable.
    Any open set <m>U \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> can be written as a disjoint union of countably many open sets (<xref ref="prop-open-sets" text="Proposition"/>), and hence is also Lebesgue measurable.
    As the Borel sets <m>\mathcal{B}</m> are the sets in the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra generated by the open sets, and each open set is in <m>\mathcal{M}</m>, it follows that <m>\mathcal{B} \subseteq \mathcal{M}</m>.</p>
</proof>
<remark>
<p>Finite sets, countably infinite sets, and intervals are all examples of Borel sets in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
    <xref ref="thm-Borel-Lebesgue-meas" text="Theorem"/> says that all Borel sets are Lebesgue measurable, but we have not exhibited any sets which are Lebesgue measurable but not Borel.</p>
<p>In the other direction, we know that <m>\mathcal{M} \subseteq \mathcal{P}(\mathbb{R})</m>, but we have not exhibited any subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m> which are not Lebesgue measurable.
    That is, we have</p>
<md> \mathcal{B} \subseteq \mathcal{M} \subseteq \mathcal{P}(\mathbb{R})</md>
<p>but it is not clear if these inclusions are strict.
    We will see in <xref ref="sec-nonmeasurable"/> that each inclusion is indeed strict: there are Lebesgue measurable sets which are not Borel sets; and there are subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m> which are not Lebesgue measurable.</p>
</remark>
<p>We will now look at some approximation and regularity properties of the Lebesgue measure. By <xref ref="prop-Lebesgue-outer-measure" text="Proposition"/> the Lebesgue outer measure <m>m^*</m> is an induced outer measure: <m>m^*</m> is the outer measure induced by the length function <m>\ell</m> on the collection of all intervals in the real line. We can thus apply <xref ref="prop-sigma-delta-sets" text="Proposition"/> to <m>m^*</m>. That is, letting <m>\mathcal{I}_{\sigma\delta}</m> be the countable intersections of countable unions of intervals, if <m>E \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> then there is a set <m>A \in \mathcal{I}_{\sigma\delta}</m> such that <m>E \subseteq A</m> and <m>m^*(A) = m^*(E)</m>. Further, if <m>E</m> is Lebesgue measurable then <m>m(A\backslash E) = 0</m> (noting here that all the sets in <m>\mathcal{I}_{\sigma\delta}</m> are Lebesgue measurable since every interval is Lebesgue measurable). The following result is a strengthening of <xref ref="prop-sigma-delta-sets" text="Proposition"/> for the Lebesgue measure.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-Leb-meas-sets-G-delta-F-sigma">
<title>Outer and inner approximation of Lebesgue measure</title>
<p><idx><h>Lebesgue measure</h><h>inner approximation</h></idx><idx><h>Lebesgue measure</h><h>outer approximation</h></idx>
    Let <m>E \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.
    The following are equivalent.</p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>E</m> is Lebesgue measurable;</p>
</li>
<li><p>for every <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m> there exists an open set <m>U</m> containing <m>E</m> such that <m>m^*(U\backslash E) &lt; \varepsilon</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p>there is a <m>G_\delta</m>-set <m>G</m> contraing <m>E</m> such that <m>m^*(G\backslash E) = 0</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p>for every <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m> there exists a closed set <m>C</m> contained in <m>E</m> such that <m>m^*(E\backslash C) &lt; \varepsilon</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p>there is an <m>F_\sigma</m>-set <m>F</m> contained in <m>E</m> such that <m>m^*(E\backslash F) = 0</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>The complement of an open set is a closed set, hence the complement of a <m>G_\delta</m> set is an <m>F_\sigma</m> set.
    Since the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of Lebesgue measurable sets is closed under complements, it follows that (ii) is equivalent to (iv) and (iii) is equivalent to (v).</p>
<p>Suppose that <m>E</m> is Lebesgue measurable. 
    We will show that (ii) holds.
    Assume <m>m(E) &lt; \infty</m>.
    Fix <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0</m>.
    By the definition of the Lebesgue outer measure <m>m^*</m>, there exists open intervals <m>\{I_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> such that <m>E \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty I_k</m> and</p>
<md> m(E) + \varepsilon &gt; \sum_{k=1}^\infty \ell(I_k).</md>
<p>Let <m>U = \bigcup_k I_k</m>. 
    Then <m>U</m> is open, <m>E \subseteq U</m>, and</p>
<md> m(U) \leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty\ell(I_k) &lt; m(E) + \varepsilon.</md>
<p>Since <m>m(U)&lt; \infty</m> we can apply the excision property (<xref ref="prop-measure-properties" text="Proposition"/>), to get
    <m>m(U\backslash E) &lt; \varepsilon</m>.
    Thus (ii) holds.
    The case when <m>m(E) = \infty</m> is left as an exercise (<xref ref="exer-outer-approx" text="Exercise"/>).</p>
<p>Now assume (ii) holds. To show (iii) holds is a similar argument to that in <xref ref="prop-sigma-delta-sets" text="Proposition"/>.
    For each <m>n</m> there is an open set <m>U_n</m> such that <m>m^*(U_n \backslash E) &lt; \frac{1}{n}</m>.
    Let <m>G</m> be the <m>G_\delta</m> set <m>G = \bigcap_n U_n</m>.
    Then <m>E \subseteq G</m> and</p>
<md> m^*(G \backslash E) \leq m^*(U_n \backslash E) &lt; \frac{1}{n}</md>
<p>for all <m>n</m>.
    Hence <m>m^*(G \backslash E) =0.</m></p>
<p>Finally, suppose that (iii) holds for a set <m>E \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.
    Take a <m>G_\delta</m> set <m>G</m> containing <m>E</m> with <m>m^*(G\backslash E) = 0</m>.
    Since <m>G</m> is a <m>G_\delta</m> set, <m>G</m> is Lebesgue measurbale; and since <m>m^*(G\backslash E) = 0</m>, <m>G \backslash E</m> is also Lebesgue measurable (<xref ref="exer-zero-measurable" text="Exercise"/>).
    Noting that</p>
<md> E = G \cap (G\backslash E)^c</md>
<p>it follows that <m>E</m> is Lebesgue measurable.</p>
</proof>
<p>The following theorem is similar to <xref ref="thm-Leb-meas-sets-G-delta-F-sigma" text="Theorem"/>. We record it however, as we will be interested in generalizations of this result in the sequel. The result describes <em>regularity</em> conditions for the Lebesgue measure.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-Lebesgue-regular">
<p>Let <m>E \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> be Lebesgue measurable, then</p>
<ol>
<li><p><em>(outer regularity)</em><idx><h>regularity of a measure</h><h>outer regularity of Lebesgue measure</h></idx>
    <md> m^*(E) = \inf \{ m(U) \colon E \subseteq U,\ U \text{ open}\};</md>
</p>
</li>
<li><p><em>(inner regularity)</em><idx><h>regularity of a measure</h><h>inner regularity of Lebesgue measure</h></idx>
    <md> m^*(E) = \sup \{ m(K) \colon K \subseteq E,\ K \text{ compact}\}.</md>
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>Condition (i) follows immediately from the definition of the Lebesgue outer measure.
    We will use condition (i) to prove (ii).</p>
<p>Take measurable <m>E \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.
    Assume first that <m>E</m> is bounded, so that <m>E \subseteq [a,b]</m> for some closed interval <m>[a,b]</m>.
    Let <m>E' = [a,b] \backslash E</m>.
    Fix <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0</m>.
    By (i), there is an open set <m>U</m> such that <m>E' \subseteq U</m> and <m>m(U) &lt; m(E') + \frac{1}{n}</m>.
    Let <m>K = [a,b] \backslash U</m>. 
    Since <m>U</m> is open, <m>K</m> is closed.
    Thus, <m>K</m> is a compact set by the Heine-Borel theorem (<xref ref="thm-heine-borel" text="Theorem"/>).
    Further, since <m>E' \subseteq U</m>, <m>K \subseteq E</m>.
    By repeated application of the excision property and monotonicity of <m>m</m>, we have</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
m(K) &amp;= (b-a) - m(U \cap [a-b]) \\
        &amp;\geq (b-a) - m(U)\\
        &amp;&gt; (b-a) - m(E') - \frac{1}{n}\\
        &amp;= (b-a) - [(b-a) - m(E)] - \frac{1}{n} \\
        &amp;= m(E) - \frac{1}{n}.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Hence</p>
<md> m(E) = \sup\{m(K) \colon K \subseteq E\text{ compact}\}.</md>
<p>The case when <m>m(E) = \infty</m> is left as an exercise (<xref ref="exer-Lebesgue-inner-reg" text="Exercise"/>).</p>
</proof>
<p>We end this section with a result (due to Lebesgue) showing the connection between the Lebesgue measure and Riemann integration.<idx><h>Riemann integration</h></idx> We first establish/recall some notation and concepts to do with Riemann integration.</p>
<p>Let <m>[a,b]</m> be a closed interval in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>, and let <m>f \colon [a,b] \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> be a bounded function. Let <m>P = \{x_0, x_1, \ldots, x_n\}</m> be a partition of <m>[a,b]</m>, where</p>
<md> a = x_0 &lt; x_1 &lt; \ldots &lt; x_n = b.</md>
<p>We define <m>O(f,P)</m> as</p>
<md> O(f,P) = \sum_{k=1}^n \sup_{x,y \in [x_{k-1},x_k]}|f(x) - f(y)|(x_k - x_{k-1})</md>
<p>The function <m>f</m> is <em>Riemann integrable</em><idx><h>integrable</h><h>Riemann integrable</h></idx> if for all <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0</m> there exists a partition <m>P</m> of <m>[a,b]</m> such that <m>O(f,P)&lt; \varepsilon</m>.<fn>You may have seen other definitions of <em>Riemann integrable</em>. Can you prove that your definition of Riemann integrable is equivalent to the definition given here?</fn></p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-Riemann-int">
<p><idx><h>integrable</h><h>Riemann integrable</h></idx>
Let <m>f</m> be a bounded function on the closed interval <m>[a,b]</m>,
and let <m>D = \{x \in [a,b] \colon f \text{ is not continuous at }x\}</m>.
Then <m>f</m> is Riemann integrable if and only if <m>D</m> has Lebesgue measure <m>0</m>.</p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>Suppose that <m>f</m> is Riemann integrable.
Take <m>x \in [a,b]</m>.
The function <m>f</m> is not continuous at <m>x</m>, if there exists <m>\varepsilon</m> such that for all <m>\delta &gt;0</m> there exists <m>y \in (x-\delta,x + \delta)\cap [a,b]</m> such that <m>|f(x)-f(y)|\geq \varepsilon</m>.
Thus, if we set</p>
<md> D_\eta = \{ x\in [a,b] \colon \forall \delta &gt;0 \exists y\in (x-\delta,x+\delta) \text{ such that }|f(x)-f(y)|\geq\eta\},</md>
<p>then</p>
<md> D = \bigcup_{\eta &gt;0} D_\eta.</md>
<p>That that, if <m>\eta_2 &gt; \eta_1 &gt; 0</m>, then <m>D_{\eta_2} \subseteq D_{\eta_1}.</m>
Thus, we can write <m>D</m> as a countable union</p>
<md> D = \bigcup_{n=1}^\infty D_{\frac{1}{n}}.</md>
<p>Fix <m>\eta &gt;0</m>. We will show that <m>m^*(D_\eta) = 0</m>.
Take any <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0</m>.
Since <m>f</m> is Riemann integrable, there exists a partition</p>
<md> P = \{a=x_0 &lt; x_1 &lt; \ldots &lt; x_n = b\}</md>
<p>such that <m>O(f,P)&lt; \varepsilon</m>.
Let <m>\Lambda = \{k \colon D_\eta \cap [x_{k-1},x_k] \neq \emptyset\}.</m>
Then</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\eta\sum_{k \in \Lambda}(x_k - x_{k-1}) &amp;\leq \sum_{k\in \Lambda} \sup_{x,y \in [x_{k-1},x_k]}|f(x)-f(y)|\\
     &amp;\leq \sum_{k=1}^n \sup_{x,y \in [x_{k-1},x_k]}|f(x)-f(y)|\\
     &amp;= O(f,P)&lt; \varepsilon.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Since <m>D_\eta \subseteq \bigcup_{k \in \Lambda} [x_{k-1},x_k]</m> it follows that</p>
<md> m^*(D_\eta) &lt; \frac{\varepsilon}{\eta}.</md>
<p>The above inequality holds for all <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>, and so <m>m^*(D_\eta) = 0</m>.
It follows that <m>D_\eta</m> is Lebesgue measurable and <m>m(D_\eta) = 0</m> (see <xref ref="exer-zero-measurable" text="Exercise"/>).
We have now that</p>
<md> m^*(D) \leq \sum_{n=1}^\infty m^*(D_{\frac{1}{n}}) = 0</md>
<p>and so <m>D</m> is also Lebesgue measurable with <m>m(D) = 0</m>.</p>
<p>Suppose now that <m>D</m> has Lebesgue measure <m>0</m>.
Given <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0</m>, there exists open intervals <m>\{I_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> such that</p>
<md> m(D) \leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \ell(I_k) &lt; \varepsilon.</md>
<p>Let <m>U = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty I_k</m> and <m>K = [a,b] \backslash U</m>.
The set <m>U</m> is a union of open intervals, and so <m>U</m> is open in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
Thus, <m>K</m> is closed.
As <m>K \subseteq [a,b]</m>, <m>K</m> is both closed and bounded, and so <m>K</m> is compact by the Heine-Borel Theorem, <xref ref="thm-heine-borel" text="Theorem"/>.</p>
<p>The function <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>[a,b]\backslash D</m>.</p>
<p>Hence, for each <m>x \in [a,b]\backslash D</m> there exists <m>\delta_x&gt;0</m> such that, for if <m>y \in [a,b]</m> and <m>|x-y|&lt;\delta_x</m> then <m>|f(x)-f(y)|&lt;\varepsilon</m>.
The open intervals <m>\{(x-\frac{\delta_x}{2}, x+\frac{\delta_x}{2})\}_{x\in K}</m> form an open cover of <m>K</m>.
Since <m>K</m> is compact, there are is a finite set <m>x_1,x_2,\ldots,x_n \in K</m> such that</p>
<md> K \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^n (x_i - \frac{\delta_{x_i}}{2}, x_i + \frac{\delta_{x_i}}{2}).</md>
<p>Let</p>
<md> P = \{a,b\} \cup (\{x_i-\frac{\delta_{x_i}}{2}, x_i + \frac{\delta_{x_i}}{2} \colon i = 1,\ldots,n\} \cap [a,b]).</md>
<p>The set <m>P</m> is finite, and contains both <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, we can thus order <m>P</m> and view <m>P</m> as a partition of <m>[a,b]</m>.
Let the ordered elements of <m>P</m> be denoted by</p>
<md> \{a=y_0 &lt; y_1 &lt;\ldots &lt; y_m = b\}.</md>
<p>Note that, if there are <m>i</m> and <m>j</m> such that <m>(x_i - \frac{\delta_{x_i}}{2}, x_i + \frac{\delta_{x_i}}{2}) \cap (y_{j-1},y_j) \neq \emptyset</m> then <m>[y_{j-1},y_j] \subseteq [x_i - \frac{\delta_{x_i}}{2}, x_i + \frac{\delta_{x_i}}{2}] \subseteq (x_i -\delta_{x_i}, x_i + \delta_{x_i})</m>.
Let</p>
<md> A = \{ j \colon \exists \ i \text{ such that }[y_{j-1},y_j] \subseteq [x_i-\frac{\delta_{x_i}}{2}, x_i + \frac{\delta_{x_i}}{2}]\} </md>
<p>and</p>
<md> B = \{ j \colon [y_{j-1},y_j] \cap (x_i-\frac{\delta_{x_i}}{2},x_i+\frac{\delta_{x_i}}{2}) = \emptyset \text{ for all }i\}. </md>
<p>Note, if <m>j \in A</m>, and <m>x,y \in [y_{i-1},y_i]</m> then</p>
<md> |f(x)-f(y)|\leq |f(x) - f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - f(x)|  &lt;2 \varepsilon,</md>
<p>for some <m>i</m>, by the choice of <m>\delta_{x_i}</m>.
Further</p>
<md> \bigcup_{j \in B} (y_{i-1},y_i) \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty I_k,</md>
<p>and so</p>
<md> \sum_{j \in B} (y_i - y_{i-1}) &lt; \varepsilon. </md>
<p>Let <m>M = \sup_{x \in [a,b]}|f(x)|</m>. Then</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
O(f,P)  =&amp; \sum_{j=1}^m \sup_{x,y \in [y_{j-1},y_j]}|f(x) - f(y)|(y_i - y_{j-1}) \\
    =&amp; \sum_{j\in A}\sup_{x,y \in [y_{j-1},y_j]}|f(x) - f(y)|(y_i - y_{j-1})\\ &amp;+ \sum_{j\in B}\sup_{x,y \in [y_{j-1},y_j]}|f(x) - f(y)|(y_i - y_{j-1})\\
    &lt;&amp; 2\varepsilon \sum_{j\in A}(y_i - y_{j-1}) + 2M \sum_{j\in B}(y_i - y_{j-1})\\
    &lt;&amp; 2\varepsilon(b-a) + 2M \varepsilon = 2\varepsilon(b-a + M).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Hence <m>f</m> is Riemann integrable.</p>
</proof>
</section>
<section xml:id="sec-nonmeasurable">
<title>Borel sets, Lebesgue measurable sets, and subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.</title>
<p>Let <m>\mathcal{B}</m> be the Borel sets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m>, and let <m>\mathcal{M}</m> be the Lebesgue measurable sets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m>. We have seen that the following inclusions hold:</p>
<md> \mathcal{B} \subseteq \mathcal{M} \subseteq \mathcal{P}(\mathbb{R}). </md>
<p>In this section we will see that both these inclusions are strict. I.e. we will see that there exist Lebesgue measurable sets which are not Borel; and there exists subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m> which are not Lebesgue measurable.</p>
<p>Another question arising from <xref ref="sec-Lebesgue"/> is the following: are there any uncountable Lebesgue measurable sets with <m>0</m> Lebesgue measure? We know that countable sets have measure <m>0</m>, but are the countable sets all of the Lebesgue measure <m>0</m> sets? We will see presently, that there are uncountable sets with Lebesgue measure <m>0</m>.</p>
<p>We will begin with proving the existence of subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m> which are not Lebesgue measurable. The following theorem was published by Giuseppe Vitali (1875 - 1932) <idx><h>Vitali, Giuseppe</h></idx> in 1905.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-Vitali-non-meas">
<title>Vitali</title>
<p>Let <m>E \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> satisfy <m>m^*(E)&gt;0</m>.
    Then there exists <m>C \subseteq E</m> such that <m>C</m> is not Lebesgue measurable.</p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>By the countable monotonicity of <m>m^*</m>,</p>
<md> m^*(E) \leq \sum_{n=1}^\infty m^*(E \cap [-n,n]).</md>
<p>Thus, <m>E</m> contains a bounded subset with positive Lebesgue outer measure.
    We can thus assume that <m>E</m> is bounded.</p>
<p>Define a relation <m>\sim_\mathbb{Q}</m> on <m>E</m> by the following rule: if <m>x,y\in E</m> then <m>x \sim_\mathbb{Q} y</m> if and only if there is a rational number <m>q \in \mathbb{Q}</m> such that <m>x - y = q</m>.
    It is not hard to see that <m>\sim_\mathbb{Q}</m> is an equivalence relation on <m>E</m> (<xref ref="exer-Q-equiv-rel" text="Exercise"/>).
    Create a set <m>C \subseteq E</m> by choosing a representative element from each equivalence class of the equivalence relation <m>\sim_\mathbb{Q}</m>.
    Thus <m>C \subseteq E</m> satisfies: if <m>x \in E</m> then there exists a unique <m>q_x \in \mathbb{Q}</m> such that <m>x+q_x \in C</m>.
    It follows that the collection of sets <m>\{C + q\}_{q \in \mathbb{Q}}</m> are disjoint and cover <m>E</m>.
    Further, as <m>E</m> is bounded (and there are infinitely many rational numbers between any two rational numbers), there is a bounded, infinite set <m>\Lambda \subseteq \mathbb{Q}</m> such that</p>
<md> E \subseteq \bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} C + \lambda. </md>
<p>Suppose now that <m>C</m> is Lebesgue measurable.
    Then, since <m>C \subseteq E</m>, <m>m(C) &lt; \infty</m>.
    Further, <m>C + \lambda</m> is Lebesgue measurable for each <m>\lambda \in \Lambda</m>, and <m>m(C + \lambda) = m(C)</m> (<xref ref="exer-Lebesgue-translation-inv" text="Exercise"/>).
    Thus, <m>\bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} C + \lambda</m> Lebesgue measurable, as it is a countable union of Lebesgue measurable sets.
    We also, have that <m>\bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} C + \lambda</m> is bounded, since <m>E</m> and <m>\Lambda</m> are bounded.
    Thus</p>
<md> \infty &gt; m(\bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} C + \lambda) = \sum_{\lambda\in \Lambda} m(C+ \lambda) = \sum_{\lambda\in \Lambda} m(C).</md>
<p>Since <m>\Lambda</m> is an infinite set, it follows that <m>m(C) = 0</m>.</p>
<p>Now, by the countable submonotonicity of the Lebesgue outer measure <m>m^*</m> we have</p>
<md> m^*(E) \leq \sum_{\lambda\in\Lambda} m(C+\lambda) = 0.</md>
<p>This contradicts, <m>m^*(E) &gt; 0</m>, and so <m>C</m> is not Lebesgue measurable.</p>
</proof>
<remark>
<p><xref ref="thm-Vitali-non-meas" text="Theorem"/> tells us that there are many subsets off <m>\mathbb{R}</m> which are not Lebesgue measurable. 
    Still, there is something unsatisfactory about the proof. 
    In the proof we construct a set <m>C</m> which is not Lebesgue measurable, but what does <m>C</m> look like?
    It is important to note that the construction of <m>C</m> given here relies on the axiom of choice.
    We <em>choose</em> and element from each equivalence class of <m>\sim_\mathbb{Q}</m>.
    This is not, however, a shortcoming of the proof.
    It is a necessity.
    There are models of set theory where the axiom of choice is not assumed, where it can be shown that all subsets of the real line are Lebesgue measurable.
    This is an interesting topic, but is too far into the weeds of set theory for what we are trying to do.
    We will (happily!) stick to the standard Zermelo–Fraenkel axioms of set theory plus the axiom of choice (ZFC).
    Thus, we are living in a world where <xref ref="thm-Vitali-non-meas" text="Theorem"/> holds.
    This won't be the last time that the axiom of choice plays a significant role in these notes; but it is perhaps the most famous and consequential.</p>
</remark>
<p>We will now embark on the construction of an uncountable subset of <m>\mathbb{R}</m> which is Lebesgue measurable with Lebesgue measure <m>0</m>.</p>
<example xml:id="ex-Cantor">
<p><idx><h>Cantor set</h></idx>
Let <m>C_0 = [0,1]</m>.
Let <m>C_1 = [0,\frac{1}{3}] \cup [\frac{2}{3},1]</m>. 
Note, that <m>C_1</m> is <m>C_0 \backslash (\frac{1}{3},\frac{2}{3})</m>. I.e. <m>C_1</m> is <m>C_0</m> with the middle third of its interval removed.
To construct <m>C_2</m> we remove the (open) middle third from each of the two disjoint intervals in <m>C_1</m>.
That is</p>
<md>C_2 = \left[0,\frac{1}{9}\right] \cup \left[\frac{2}{9},\frac{1}{3}\right]\cup\left[\frac{2}{3},\frac{7}{9}\right]\cup\left[\frac{8}{9},1\right].</md>
<p>We construct <m>C_3</m> by removing the open middle thirds from each of the 4 intervals in <m>C_2</m>.
We continue in this way: <m>C_n</m> is constructed from <m>C_{n-1}</m> by removing the open middle thirds from each of the <m>2^{n-1}</m> closed intervals in <m>C_{n-1}</m>.</p>
<p><figure xml:id="fig-cantor-set">
<image source="images/Cantor.jpg" width="25%" />
<caption>
  <p>Illustration of the sets <m>C_0</m> (top), <m>C_1, \ldots</m> used to construct the Cantor set <m>C</m>.</p>
</caption>
</figure>
</p>
<p>Let <m>C = \bigcap_{n=0}^\infty C_n</m>.
We call <m>C</m> the <em>Cantor set</em>.<idx><h>Cantor set</h></idx><fn>The set <m>C</m> is also referred to as the <em>Cantor middle-third set</em>.</fn>
Since each <m>C_n</m> is a closed set, <m>C</m> is also a closed set (as intersections of closed sets are closed sets).
It follows that <m>C</m> is a Borel set, and hence <m>C</m> is Lebesgue measurable.</p>
<p>Let <m>U_k</m> be the open set which is removed from <m>C_{k-1}</m> to get <m>C_k</m>.
Thus, <m>U_1 = (1/3,2/3)</m>, <m>U_2 = (1/9,2/9) \cup (7/9,8/9)</m>, etc.
Let <m>U = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty U_k</m>.
Note that</p>
<md> m(U_k) = \frac{2^{k-1}}{3^k}.</md>
<p>As the sets <m>\{U_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> are disjoint, we have that</p>
<md> m(U) = \sum_{k=1}^\infty \frac{2^{k-1}}{3^k} = \frac{1}{3}\sum_{k=0}^\infty \frac{2^{k}}{3^k} = 1.</md>
<p>Now, as <m>[0,1] = U \cup C</m>, and <m>\ell([0,1])=1</m>, it follows that <m>m(C) = 0</m>.</p>
<p>We will now look at the cardinality of <m>C</m>.
Every number in <m>[0,1]</m> has a binary expansion.
If we do not consider finite binary expansions, and only consider infinite expansions, the binary expansions are unique.<fn>That is we will write the binary expansion <m>0.1</m> as <m>0.011111\ldots</m>.</fn>
Suppose <m>c \in C</m>. 
Construct <m>f(c) \in [0,1]</m> be the following algorithm: if <m>c</m> is in the left half <m>C_1</m>, then the first digit in the binary expansion of <m>f(c)</m> is <m>0</m>; if <m>c</m> is in the right interval of <m>C_1</m> then the first digit of the binary expansion of <m>f(c)</m> is <m>1</m>.
Now, in <m>C_2</m>, <m>f(c)</m> is in either the left subinterval, or the right subinterval of the interval <m>c</m> is in <m>C_0</m>.
Let <m>0</m> be the second digit of <m>f(c)</m> if <m>c</m> is to the left, <m>1</m> be the second digit if <m>c</m> is to the right.
Continuing in this way we get <m>f(c)</m> as a binary expansion.
The map <m>f</m> is a bijection from <m>C</m> to <m>[0,1]</m>, hence <m>C</m> and <m>[0,1]</m> have the same cardinality.
As <m>[0,1]</m> is uncountable<fn>This is traditionally proved using the famed diagonal argument of Cantor. We also know that <m>[0,1]</m> is uncountable since <m>m([0,1]) = 1</m> and countable sets have Lebesgue measure <m>0</m> by <xref ref="thm-countable-L-measurable" text="Theorem"/>.</fn>, it follows that <m>C</m> is uncountable.</p>
</example>
<p>We thus shown have that the Cantor set <m>C</m> has Lebesgue measure <m>0</m> and is uncountable.<idx><h>Cantor set</h></idx> Hence the converse of <xref ref="thm-countable-L-measurable" text="Theorem"/> does not hold. All countable sets have Lebesgue measure <m>0</m>, but not all Lebesgue measure <m>0</m> sets are countable.</p>
<p>We want to prove the existence of Lebesgue measurable sets which are not Borel sets. In order to do this we first introduce a function, the <em>Cantor-Lebesgue function</em>.<idx><h>Cantor-Lebesgue function</h></idx> Whilst we introduce it now for the purpose of finding a set which is not Borel, the Cantor-Lebesgue function is of interest in its own right.</p>
<example xml:id="ex-cantor-lebesgue">
<p>Let <m>C</m> be the Cantor set, from <xref ref="ex-Cantor" text="Example"/>, and let <m>U = [0,1]\backslash C</m>.
    We first define a function <m>\varphi</m> on <m>U</m>.
    Recall that <m>U = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty U_k</m> where <m>U_k</m> is the open set removed from <m>C_k</m> at the <m>kth</m> step of the construction of the Cantor set <m>C</m>.</p>
<p>Let <m>\varphi(x) = 1/2</m> for <m>x \in U_1 = (1/3,2/3)</m>.
    For <m>x \in U_2</m> define <m>\varphi(x)</m> by</p>
<md>
\varphi(x) = \begin{cases} \frac{1}{4} &amp; x \in (1/9,2/9) \\
        \frac{3}{4} &amp; x \in (7/9,8/9).
        \end{cases}
</md>
<p>Continue in this way, so that for <m>x \in U_k</m></p>
<md> \varphi(x) = \frac{2m-1}{2^k}</md>
<p>when <m>x</m> is in the <m>m</m>th interval in <m>U_k</m> (See Figure~\ref{fig: cantor lebesgue}).</p>
<p><figure xml:id="fig-cantor-lebesgue">
<image source="images/Cantor-Lebesgue.png" width="25%" />
<caption>
  <p>The Cantor-Lebesgue function on the set <m>U</m>.</p>
</caption>
</figure>
</p>
<p>We extend <m>\varphi</m> to all of <m>[0,1]</m> by setting <m>\varphi(0)=0</m>, and for <m>x \in C\backslash\{0\}</m>,</p>
<md> \varphi(x) = \sup\{\varphi(y) \colon y \in [0,x) \cap U \}.</md>
<p>We call <m>\varphi</m> the <em>Cantor-Lebesgue function</em><idx><h>Cantor-Lebesgue function</h></idx>
    Note that <m>\varphi</m> is continuous.
    Indeed, <m>\varphi</m> is clearly continuous on <m>U</m>, since <m>\varphi</m> is constant on open intervals in <m>U</m>.
    For <m>x \in C</m>, and <m>K</m> large enough, we can find <m>a_k &lt; x &lt; b_k</m> such that</p>
<md>\varphi(b_k) - \varphi(a_k) &lt; \frac{1}{2^k}</md>
<p>for all <m>k\geq K</m>.
    It follows that <m>\varphi</m> does not have a jump discontinuity at <m>x</m>.
    As <m>\varphi</m> is increasing, this shows that <m>\varphi</m> is continuous at <m>x</m>.</p>
</example>
<lemma xml:id="lem-non-Borel">
<p>Let <m>C</m> be the Cantor set.
    Then there is a set <m>A \subseteq C</m> such that <m>A</m> is Lebesgue measurable but <m>A</m> is not a Borel set.</p>
</lemma>
<proof>
<p>Let <m>\varphi</m> be the Cantor-Lebesgue function from <xref ref="ex-cantor-lebesgue" text="Example"/>.<idx><h>Cantor-Lebesgue function</h></idx>
    The function <m>\varphi</m> is an increasing, continuous function with <m>\varphi(0) = 0</m> and <m>\varphi(1) = 1</m>.
    It follows from the Intermediate Value Theorem that <m>\varphi</m> maps <m>[0,1]</m> surjectively onto <m>[0,1]</m>.
    Define a function <m>\psi \colon [0,1] \rightarrow [0,2]</m> by</p>
<md> \psi(x) = \varphi(x) + x.</md>
<p>Then <m>\psi</m> is a continuous, strictly increasing function with <m>\psi([0,1]) = [0,2]</m>.</p>
<p>Let <m>C \subseteq [0,1]</m> be the Cantor set, and let <m>U = [0,1] \backslash U</m>.
    By <xref ref="ex-Cantor" text="Example"/>, <m>m(C) = 0</m>, and hence <m>m(U) = 1</m>.
    Applying <m>\psi</m> to <m>C</m> and <m>U</m> we get disjoint sets <m>\psi(C)</m> and <m>\psi(U)</m> satisfying</p>
<md> [0,2] = \psi(C) \cup \psi(U). </md>
<p>Recall that <m>\varphi</m> is constructed so that there are disjoint open intervals <m>\{I_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> such that <m>U = \bigcup_k I_k</m> and <m>\varphi</m> is constant on each <m>I_k</m>.
    Let <m>c_k = \varphi(x)</m> when <m>c \in I_k</m>.
    Then, <m>\psi(I_k) = c_k + I_k</m>.
    Hence <m>\psi(U) = \bigcup_k(c_k + I_k)</m> is a countable union of intervals, and hence <m>\psi(U)</m> is Lebesgue measurable.
    Further</p>
<md> m(\psi(U)) = \sum_{k=1}^\infty \ell(c_k + I_k) = \sum_{k=1}^\infty \ell(c_k + I_k) = m(U) = 1.</md>
<p>As <m>[0,2]</m> and <m>\psi(U)</m> are Lebesgue measurable, it follows that <m>\psi(C)</m> is Lebesgue measurable, and <m>m(\psi(C)) = m([0,2]) - m(\psi(U)) = 1.</m></p>
<p><xref ref="thm-Vitali-non-meas" text="Theorem"/> tells us that there is a set <m>B \subseteq \psi(C)</m> which is not Lebesgue measurable.</p>
<p>Since <m>\psi</m> is strictly increasing bijection from <m>[0,1]</m> to <m>[0,2]</m> it has a continuous inverse <m>\psi^{-1} \colon [0,2] \rightarrow [0,1]</m> (<xref ref="exer-cont-inverse" text="Exercise"/>).
    Let <m>A = \psi^{-1}(B) \subseteq C</m>.
    As <m>\psi(A) = B</m> is not Lebesgue measurable, and hence not a Borel set, it follows from <xref ref="exer-Borel-inv-img" text="Exercise"/> that <m>A</m> is not a Borel set.
    As <m>A \subseteq C</m> and <m>m(C) = 0</m>, <m>A</m> is a Lebesgue measurable since <m>(\mathbb{R}, \mathcal{M}, m)</m> is a complete measure space.</p>
</proof>
<theorem>
<p>The <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of Borel subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m> is strictly contained in the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of Lebesgue measurable subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>That the Borel sets <m>\mathcal{B}</m> are contained in the Lebesgue measurable sets <m>\mathcal{M}</m> is <xref ref="thm-Borel-Lebesgue-meas" text="Theorem"/>.
    <xref ref="lem-non-Borel" text="Lemma"/> gives the existence of a Lebesgue measurable set which is not Borel.</p>
</proof>
<corollary>
<p>The measure space <m>(\mathbb{R},\mathcal{B},m)</m> of the Lebesgue measure restricted to the Borel sets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m> is not a complete measure space.</p>
</corollary>
<proof>
<p>The Cantor set <m>C</m> is closed, and hence a Borel set.
    Further <m>m(C)=0</m>.
    <xref ref="lem-non-Borel" text="Lemma"/> shows that there is a set <m>A \subseteq C</m> which is not a Borel set, hence <m>(\mathbb{R},\mathcal{B},m)</m> is not a complete measure space.</p>
</proof>
</section>
<section xml:id="sec-borel-on-R">
<title>Borel measures on <m>\mathbb{R}</m></title>
<p>The Lebesgue measure <m>m</m> is induced by the length function on intervals: <m>\ell((c,d])) = d - c</m>. Given an increasing function <m>g</m> on <m>\mathbb{R}</m> we can define a weighted length on intervals by <m>\mu((a,b]) = g(b) - g(a)</m>. We in this section we show how, with some reasonable constraints on <m>g</m>, this gives rise to a Borel measure. Conversely, we show how Borel measures on <m>\mathbb{R}</m> give rise to functions. These processes will be, up to the addition of a constant, inverses of each other.</p>
<p>We will begin with constructing functions from Borel measures.</p>
<definition xml:id="def-cumulative-dist">
<p>Let <m>I</m> be a closed interval in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
Let <m>\mu</m> be a finite Borel measure on <m>I</m>.
Define a function <m>g_\mu \colon I \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> by</p>
<md> g_\mu(x) = \mu(\{y \in I \colon y\leq x\}).</md>
<p>The function <m>g_\mu</m> is called the <em>cumulative distribution function</em> for <m>\mu</m>.<idx><h>cumulative distribution function</h></idx></p>
</definition>
<remark xml:id="rem-cumulative-dist-in-probability">
<p>The term <em>cumulative distribution function</em> is borrowed from probability theory.</p>
</remark>
<example xml:id="exam-cdf-of-gaussian">
<p><idx><h>distribution</h><h>Gaussian distribution</h></idx>
Let <m>\gamma</m> be the Gaussian distribution.
The cumulative distribution function of <m>\gamma</m> is usually denoted by <m>\Phi</m>.
By definition <m>\Phi</m> is given by</p>
<md>\Phi(x) = \gamma((-\infty,x]) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} \int_{-\infty}^x e^\frac{-x^2}{2}.</md>
<p>Note that <m>\Phi</m> is continuous on every closed interval <m>[a,b]</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
Further,</p>
<md> \Phi'(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} e^{\frac{-x^2}{2}}.</md>
<p><figure xml:id="fig-gaussian-cdf">
<image source="images/Gaussian cdf.png" width="25%" />
</figure>
</p>
</example>
<p>A cumulative distribution functions need not be continuous, but they will satisfy a one-sided version of continuity. We define this formally now, before showing all cumulative distribution functions satisfy it in <xref ref="thm-cdf" text="Theorem"/>.</p>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>I \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> be a closed interval. 
A function <m>g \colon I \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> is <em>right-continuous</em> on <m>I</m><idx><h>continuous function</h><h>right-continuous</h></idx> if given <m>x_0 \in I</m> such that there exists <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m> such that <m>x_0 + \varepsilon \in I</m> (i.e. <m>x_0</m> is not a right end-point of <m>I</m>), then</p>
<md> \lim_{x \rightarrow x_0^+} g(x) = g(x_0). </md>
</definition>
<theorem xml:id="thm-cdf">
<p><idx><h>cumulative distribution function</h></idx>
Let <m>I \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> be a closed interval and let <m>\mu</m> be a finite Borel measure on <m>I</m>.
Then the cumulative distribution function <m>g_\mu</m> for <m>\mu</m> is increasing and right-continuous.</p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>Let <m>\mu</m> be a finite Borel measure on <m>I</m> and let <m>g = g_\mu</m> be the corresponding cumulative distribution function.
    Note that, if <m>a, b \in I</m> with <m>a&lt;b</m> then</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
g(b) - g(a) &amp;= \mu(\{x \in I \colon x \leq b\}) - \mu(\{x \in I \colon x \leq a\})\\
    &amp;= \mu((a,b]) \geq 0.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Thus, <m>g</m> is an increasing function.</p>
<p>We will now show that <m>g</m> is right-continuous.
    Take <m>x_0 \in I</m>, such that there is a <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m> such that <m>x_0 + \varepsilon \in I</m>.
    Let <m>(x_k)_k</m> be a sequence in <m>I</m> converging to <m>x_0</m>, with <m>x_k &gt; x_0</m> for each <m>k</m>.
    Then</p>
<md> \bigcap_{k=1}^\infty (x_0,x_k] = \emptyset.</md>
<p>Hence, since <m>\mu</m> is a finite measure, continuity of measure, <xref ref="thm-continuity-of-measure" text="Theorem"/>, gives</p>
<md> 0 = \mu(\emptyset) = \lim_{k\rightarrow \infty} \mu((x_0,x_k]) = \lim_{k \rightarrow \infty} [g(x_k) - g(x_0)].</md>
<p>Hence <m>g</m> is right-continuous.</p>
</proof>
<p>We will now show how a Borel measure can be recovered from its cumulative distribution function. More generally, we show that any increasing, right-continuous function defines a Borel measure.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-lebesgue-stieltjes-measure">
<p>Let <m>I \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> be a closed interval, and let <m>g \colon I \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> be a non-negative, increasing, right-continuous function.
If <m>I</m> has a minimal element we will also assume that <m>g</m> is non-negative.
Then there is a unique Borel measure <m>\mu_g</m> on <m>I</m> satisfying <m>\mu_g((c,d]) = g(d) - g(c).</m></p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>First assume that <m>I</m> does not have a minimal element.
That is, assume <m>I = (-\infty,b]</m> for some <m>b</m>, or <m>I = \mathbb{R}</m>.
Let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be the semiring of subsets of <m>I</m>,</p>
<md> \mathcal{S} = \{ (c,d] \colon c,d \in I,\ c&lt;d \} \cup \{\emptyset\}.</md>
<p>Define <m>\mu</m> on <m>\mathcal{S}</m> by <m>\mu(\emptyset) = 0</m> and <m>\mu((c,d]) = g(d)- g(c).</m>
We will show that <m>\mu</m> is a premeasure on <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.
It is straightforward to show that</p>
<md> \mu((c,d]) = \sum_{k=1}^n \mu((c_k,d_k]]</md>
<p>if <m>\{(c_k,d_k]\}_{k=1}^n</m>  are disjoint intervals in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> with <m>(c,d] = \bigcup_k (c_k,d_k]</m>.</p>
<p>It remains to show that <m>\mu</m> is countably monotonic.
Suppose <m>(c,d]</m> and <m>\{(c_k,d_k]\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> are in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> and satisfy</p>
<md> (c,d] \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty (c_k,d_k]. </md>
<p>Fix <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0</m> such that <m>c+ \varepsilon &lt; d</m>.
For each <m>k</m>, choose <m>d_k'</m> such that <m>d_k &lt; d_k'</m> and</p>
<md> g(d_k') - g(d_k) &lt; \frac{\varepsilon}{2^k} .</md>
<p>(if <m>d_k</m> is the end-point of <m>I</m> for some <m>k</m> we can extend <m>g</m> so that <m>g(x) - g(d_k)</m> for <m>x &gt; d_k</m>).
Note that we can <m>d_k'</m> by the right continuity of <m>g</m>.
We now have the following inclusions</p>
<md>[c+\varepsilon,d] \subseteq (c,d] \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty (c_k,d_k] \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty (c_k,d_k').</md>
<p>Thus, <m>\{(c_k,d_k')\}_k</m> is an open cover of <m>[c+\varepsilon,d]</m>.
By the Heine-Borel Theorem, <m>[c+\varepsilon,d]</m> is compact, thus there is a finite subcover of <m>[c+\varepsilon, d]</m>.
We (relabelling if necessary) denote the sets in this subcover by <m>(c_1,d_1'),\ldots,(c_n,d_n').</m>
As <m>g</m> is increasing, it follows that</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
g(d) - g(c+\varepsilon)&amp;\leq \sum_{k=1}^n g(d_k') - g(c_k) \\
&amp; &lt; \sum_{k=1}^n [g(d_k) - g(c_k) + \frac{\varepsilon}{2^k}] \\
&amp; &lt; \sum_{k=1}^\infty [g(d_k) - g(c_k) + \frac{\varepsilon}{2^k}]\\
&amp; = \sum_{k=1}^\infty  [g(d_k) - g(c_k)] + \varepsilon.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Taking a limit as <m>\varepsilon</m> goes to <m>0</m> (from above), the right continuity of <m>g</m> gives that</p>
<md> g(d) - g(c) \leq  \sum_{k=1}^\infty  [g(d_k) - g(c_k)],</md>
<p>and so <m>\mu</m> is countably monotonic.
Hence <m>\mu</m> is a premeasure on <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.</p>
<p>When <m>I</m> has a minimal element <m>a</m>, so that <m>I = [a,b]</m> or <m>I = [a,\infty)</m> we define <m>\mathcal{S}</m> to be</p>
<md> \mathcal{S} = \{a\} \cup \{ (c,d] \colon c,d \in I,\ c&lt;d \} \cup \{\emptyset\}.</md>
<p>We define <m>\mu</m> as above with the extra condition <m>\mu(\{a\}) = g(a)</m>.
Again, <m>\mu</m> will be a premeasure on the semiring <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.</p>
<p>In both cases, the Carathéodory-Hahn Theorem says that <m>\mu</m> extends to a measure on <m>I</m>, which we will still denote by <m>\mu</m>.
The uniqueness of <m>\mu</m> follows again from the Carathéodory-Hahn Theorem, and the fact that <m>\mu</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite on <m>I</m>.
As the sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> will be <m>\mu</m>-measurable, the Borel sets will be measurable with respect to <m>\mu</m>.
If <m>K = [c,d]</m> is a closed interval in <m>I</m>, then <m>\mu([c,d]) &lt; \infty</m>.
It follows that <m>\mu(K) &lt; \infty</m> for any compact set <m>K</m>, and thus <m>\mu</m> defines a Borel measure on <m>I</m>.</p>
</proof>
<remark>
<p>When <m>I = \mathbb{R}</m> and <m>g(x) = x</m>,  the measure <m>\mu_g</m> constructed by <xref ref="thm-cdf" text="Theorem"/> is the Lebesgue measure.</p>
</remark>
<corollary xml:id="cor-lebesgue-stieltjes-measure">
<p>Let <m>I</m> be a closed interval in <m>\mathbb{R}</m> and let <m>g</m> be a non-negative, increasing, right-continuous function on <m>I</m>.
If <m>I</m> is not bounded below, further assume <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty}g(x) = 0</m>.
Let <m>\mu_g</m> be the Borel measure on <m>I</m> satisfying <m>\mu_g((c,d]) = g(d) - g(c)</m> constructed in <xref ref="thm-lebesgue-stieltjes-measure" text="Theorem"/>.</p>
<p>If <m>\mu_g</m> is a finite Borel measure then <m>g</m> is the cumulative distribution function for <m>\mu_g</m>.</p>
</corollary>
<proof>
<p>Suppose <m>a</m> is the minimal element of <m>I</m>.
Then, for each <m>x \in I</m>, the construction of <m>\mu_g</m> in <xref ref="thm-cdf" text="Theorem"/> gives</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu(\{y \in I \colon y \leq x \} &amp;= \mu([a,x]) \\
    &amp;= \mu(\{a\}) + \mu((a,x]) \\
    &amp;= g(a) + (g(x) - g(a)) = g(x).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Thus, <m>g</m> is the cumulative distribution function for <m>\mu_g</m>.</p>
<p>Now suppose <m>I</m> is not bounded below and that <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} g(x) = 0.</m>
Fix <m>x \in I</m>.
Then</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu((-\infty,x]) &amp;= \mu\left(\bigcup_{-n&lt;x} (-n,x]\right) \\
    &amp;= \lim_n \mu((-n,x]) \\
    &amp;= g(x) - \lim_n g(-n) \\
    &amp;= g(x),
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>and hence <m>g</m> is the cumulative distribution function for <m>\mu_g</m>.</p>
</proof>
<corollary xml:id="cor-cdf-and-Borel">
<p>Let <m>[a,b]</m> be a closed bounded interval in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
Every Borel measure on <m>[a,b]</m> is uniquely determined by its cumulative distribution function.</p>
</corollary>
</section>
<exercises>
<exercise>
<p>Let <m>m</m> be the Lebesgue measure on <m>\mathbb{R}</m>. Suppose <m>E \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> is Lebesgue measurable.
Take <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>.
Show that there are disjoint Lebesgue measure able sets <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> such that</p>
<md> E = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty E_k</md>
<p>and <m>m(E_k)&lt;\varepsilon</m> for each <m>k</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-Lebesgue-translation-inv">
<p>Let <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>. Show that <m>m^*(A) = m^*(A + \lambda)</m> for all <m>\lambda \in \mathbb{R}</m>.
    Show that <m>A</m> is Lebesgue measurable if and only if <m>A + \lambda</m> is Lebesgue measurable for all <m>\lambda \in \mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-outer-approx">
<p>Complete the proof of <xref ref="thm-Leb-meas-sets-G-delta-F-sigma" text="Theorem"/>.
    That is, show that if <m>E</m> is measurable  then for all <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m> there is an open set <m>U</m> containing <m>E</m> such that <m>m(U\backslash E) &lt; \varepsilon</m>.
    (You can assume that the result holds when <m>m(E)&lt;\infty</m>; the proof of that case is given in the proof of <xref ref="thm-Leb-meas-sets-G-delta-F-sigma" text="Theorem"/>).</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-Lebesgue-inner-reg">
<p>Complete the proof of <xref ref="thm-Lebesgue-regular" text="Theorem"/>.
    That is, show that if <m>E \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> is Lebesgue measurable then</p>
<md> m(E) = \sup\{m(K) \colon K \subseteq E,\ K\text{ compact}\}.</md>
<p>(The case when <m>m(E)&lt;\infty</m> is given in the proof of <xref ref="thm-Lebesgue-regular" text="Theorem"/>).</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-Q-equiv-rel">
<p>Let <m>E \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> be a subset, and let <m>\sim_\mathbb{Q}</m> be the relation defined in <xref ref="thm-Vitali-non-meas" text="Theorem"/>.
    That is, <m>x \sim_\mathbb{Q} y</m> if and only if there is a <m>q \in \mathbb{Q}</m> such that <m>x = y + q</m>.
    Show that <m>\sim_\mathbb{Q}</m> is an equivalence relation.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-cont-inverse">
<p>Let <m>\psi \colon [a,b] \rightarrow [c,d]</m> be a strictly increasing continuous bijection.
Show that <m>\psi</m> has a continuous inverse.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-Borel-inv-img">
<p>Let <m>f \colon \mathbb{R} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> be a continuous function.
Show that <m>f^{-1}(B)</m> for any Borel set <m>B \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-dirac-cdf">
<p>Let <m>\delta_0</m> be the Dirac measure on the Borel sets <m>\mathbb{B}</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}</m> (<xref ref="exer-dirac-meas" text="Example"/>).
That is, for <m>A \in \mathcal{B}</m>, <m>\delta_0(A) = 0</m> if <m>0 \notin A</m>, and <m>\delta_0(A) = 1</m> if <m>0 \in A</m>.
Find the cumulative distribution function <m>H</m> for <m>\delta_0</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise>
<p>Let <m>(\mathbb{R},\mathcal{B},m)</m> be the measure space of the Lebesgue measure restricted to the Borel sets <m>\mathcal{B}</m>.
    Let <m>(\mathbb{R}, \mathcal{B}_0, m_0)</m> be the completion of <m>(\mathbb{R},\mathcal{B},m)</m>.
    Show that <m>\mathcal{B}_0 = \mathcal{M}</m>, the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of all Lebesgue measurable sets; and that <m>m_0 = m</m>, the Lebesgue measure.
    I.e., show that the completion of the Lebesgue measure restricted to the Borel sets, is the Lebesgue measure on all Lebesgue measurable sets.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-cant-len-func-singular">
<p>Let <m>\varphi</m> be the Cantor Lebesgue function on <m>[0,1]</m>, let <m>C</m> be the Cantor set, and let <m>U = [0,1] \backslash C</m>.
Show that <m>\varphi'(x) = 0</m> for all <m>x \in U</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-cantor-leb-cdf">
<p>Let <m>C \subseteq [0,1]</m> be the Cantor set; let <m>U = [0,1]\backslash C</m>; and let <m>\varphi \colon [0,1] \rightarrow [0,1]</m>.
Let <m>\mu</m> be the Borel measure on <m>[0,1]</m> induced by <m>\varphi</m> (using <xref ref="thm-lebesgue-stieltjes-measure" text="Theorem"/>).
Show that <m>\mu([0,1]) = 1</m>; <m>\mu(C) = 1</m> and <m>\mu(U) = 0</m>.</p>
</exercise>
</exercises>
</chapter>
